{
  "doc_id": "38973",
  "text": "Metrics: We evaluated the segmentation performance with PK [CITATION_1] and WindowDiff (WD r ) [CITATION_2] , which are two common metrics used in topic segmentation. Both move a sliding window of fixed size k over the document, and compare the inferred segmentation with the gold-standard segmentation for each window. The window size is usually set to the half of the average gold-standard segment size [CITATION_3] . In addition, we also used an extended WindowDiff proposed by [CITATION_4] , denoted by WD e . One problem of WD r is that errors near the two ends of a text are penalised less than those in the middle. To solve the problem WD e adds k fictive text passages at the beginning and the end of the text when computing the score. We evaluated all the methods with the same Java code for the three metrics.",
